sim_txt_supports:
More than one contribution of ideas or expectations from each student to ensure everyone is engaged with the discussion at hand
A tangible product that can be created (poster, other visual aid, etc.) so that students can know what is expected of them at all times 
More input from me rather than students about what should be (I set the big expectation and they elaborate on how to act it out, e.g.) so that I maintain authority in the class as teacher while students feel they know how to live up to my expectations/our norms
sim_txt_beneficial:
Culmination of multiple times practicing the same scenarios allowed me to know specific tips to get through (direct commands to stop inappropriate behavior rather than questions, e.g.)

sim_txt_fbsk: When discussing the first question, one of the students answered that Lisa probably felt nervous about her lie detector results. I prompted the student further to see why the thought that she felt nervous. One student disagreed and said that she felt excited and not nervous. After he explained why he thought that, I clarified that the example/information he used was from an earlier portion of the text. I then asked why she had to falsify her lie detector results which the students could not answer. When discussing who Lisa really was, one student answered "reporter" while another answered "spy," and they both agreed that she wasn't really an intern. This allowed me to clarify for them that her lie about her reason for joining the company was the reason that she had to falsify her lie detector results.
sim_txt_cmsk: I asked the students what they thought that the classroom should look like, and they gave me their own opinions/answers. Additionally, I tried to involve all of the students in providing both expectations and the rationales behind them. This was because I wanted all the students to get a chance to voice their opinions.
sim_txt_eth_behavior: Disruptive, talkative, doesn't listen even when repeatedly asked to quiet down
sim_txt_eth_contribute: It could be that Ethan has some kind of behavioral disorder that keeps him from paying attention for long periods of time (like ADHD or something similar.) I would want to know prior background about this student from past and current teachers to see if he has behaved this way before. I would also want to know if he had been diagnosed with any disorders that could impede his focus.
sim_txt_supports:
'- teacher may need information about whether or not one of their students has been diagnosed with a behavioral disorder
- students may need to understand the reasons that a student behaves in a certain way
- quiet space where students could go
- variable assignments that play to students strengths
- short time before or during class where they could talk about their interests (like Star Wars and Spongebob)
sim_txt_beneficial: It was a good way to practice probing students using their own responses as well as dealing with behavioral issues.
sim_txt_improve_exp: Knowing the set-up of the overall simulator (like the 1-5-5 minute sessions). It made me nervous to see the 25 minute time slot on the sign up.
sim_txt_concerns: Knowing the best ways to divide teacher versus classroom expectations. I wanted the students to be able to voice their own opinions, but I wanted my own rules to be followed as well.

sim_txt_supports:
'-Well, we need rules already established.
-Students also need a clear sense of the classroom boundaries: when they are allowed to be silly or chatty vs. when they need to be focused on academic work
sim_txt_beneficial: It is beneficial to learn a specific strategy from the coach and then get to try to practice it.  I'm glad to add his advice to my fund of knowledge.
sim_txt_improve_exp: I'm starting to have mixed feelings about the simulator.  I think it is an effective enough idea for practicing instructional approaches for small group setting,  but the classroom management scenario feels much more forced.  It feels like there is one specific way to get Ethan to stop his behavior (give a timely and specific order), but of course you don't know this your first time around.  The coach then tells you exactly what to do, and the next go around, Ethan magically responds.  It seems the goal is not to manage but to find the management technique you need to "beat" the simulator.   If this is the management technique you want us to learn, why not just tell us that?  Why not just have the coach come to our class as a whole and give this instruction and modeling?  It also odd, that given the extreme and constant emphasis in Curry on classroom culture, norms, and preventative action, that we would suddenly be asked to do management devoid of all of this and instead manage after-the-fact.  I wish that after-the-fact management would be covered more in our courses.
name: Riddle,Hannah Webb

I would want to know in this context if he might have a diagnosis of ADD or ADHD, and if there were any particular ways that he was learning to redirect his difficulty concentrating.

sim_txt_supports: I think that removing cell phones from the classroom would be a start for setting up a more productive environment. sim_txt_supports:
1. Visualized reminders: I think having a reminder in the classroom of  how to and when to interact with each other is important for students.
2. A routine: If students have a set structure and routine, they will be less likely to have unproductive encounters with other students because they have designated time for socialization. 
3. Solicited peer interactions: When completing group assignments, it's important to have students be able to talk with each other in a comfortable and designated space. Think-Pair-Share is important for fostering an engaging classroom community.

sim_txt_cmsk: We got nothing accomplished the first time around. The second time, I got a few responses from students with suggestions for guiding principles for our classroom. If this were a real classroom, I would have been able to write them on the board behind me as points of reference and to build off of. and honestly, to help me remember them, but in this awkward situation, my discomfort got in the way of that.
sim_txt_eth_behavior: He had great ideas but a lot of energy and needed something with which to channel it like pencil and paper to draw his ideas or a fidget.

sim_txt_supports: Time to build relationships. Activities with which to ground the learning or the lesson. Visual supports. A whiteboard/chalkboard. A way for students to get up and be engaged and active in the lesson rather than sitting the whole time. A way for me to have an anchor chart or the materials with which to make one.
sim_txt_beneficial: It forced me to be concise and quick even though I wasn't able to do this well.
sim_txt_improve_exp: I would rather teach in a real classroom any day.
sim_txt_concerns: This is my third time in the simulator and I wish I could have a sense of humor about it but I find it incredibly frustrating and demoralizing. There has never been any coaching element, so if there was some way that this was a learning experience for me, that would make it feel a little more bearable. Instead, it feels humiliating. And I think the very real dynamic and physical aspects of teaching and of getting to walk over and get down on a students' level and look them in the eye or touch their shoulder or calmly place my hand over their hand are really invaluable. And having context for a lesson would be invaluable. I don't think it's realistic at all that we would create classroom norms and expectations in 5 minutes. And we'd have already had some time briefly getting to know students by home visits or meet-your-teacher open house or even just in the hallway and as they unpack their backpack so we could be hard at work creating connections and building relationships. Our Classroom Management class and The First 6 Weeks of School text coach us to root norms and expectations in the hopes and dreams of the students after our first week getting them used to the school, reviewing procedures, and having them begin to trust each other and me. In the 5 minute simulator, that all goes out the window.

sim_txt_beneficial: It brought weakness right into focus. I am really frustrated that there's no feedback component. I get it that I now know what to think about and focus on learning in the months ahead, but I also feel unsupported.
sim_txt_improve_exp:
Feedback right then and there.

Prior notice that I'd be leading a class on the first day of school on setting classroom expectations. That felt like a huge sabotage and I resent it. I think if a professor were there to offer feedback and guidance so I could improve my behavior management and classroom management skills, this could be really helpful. As of right now, I feel like it just makes me feel bad.
sim_txt_concerns: How am I supposed to get feedback to improve? Am I just supposed to be more motivated to figure it out in the weeks ahead in our classes? It was my understanding that this is what this experience was supposed to be.

sim_txt_eth_behavior:
Disruptive and inconsiderate, but at the same time he did not seem aware of the fact that his actions were not appropriate.  He made a comment about not recognizing that whistling was not okay, and he seemed genuinely surprised when informed that drumming and beat boxing were not appropriate noises in the classroom either.  
He wanted to be able to share his stories and did not recognize that the classroom was not the appropriate place for his actions.
sim_txt_eth_contribute:
He seemed bored.
He wanted to be somewhere else.

He was not interested in wholly participating in the activity.  
I wanted to provide him with the opportunity share, but without him really engaging or even stopping long enough to talk with me, I had a difficult time from the management side.  I would like to have the opportunity to talk with him one on one in a calm environment.  Hopefully having a conversation that helps expose him to the needs of others, and how his actions impacted them, then we could bolster a working partnership that helps the entire class.
sim_txt_supports:
Personal relationships.  By not being able to have a personal relationship that allows for me to support Ethan and his actions, I have a hard time improving the classroom climate.  
Legitimate classroom expectations.  As we are able to have a positive relationship, then we can put into place a set of expectations that are reasonable and supported by all of the students.  And without first having a relationship, then I can not help the student to improve in the class.
Discipline referrals are not the way to go in this case because Ethan was not combative, temperamental, or otherwise disruptive for the sake of being disruptive.  He just was not recognizing that his actions were disruptive.
sim_txt_beneficial: Reflecting on how to respond.  Reflecting on teaching is important, and this was a beneficial experience to have, reflect, and then redo.  Because this was a time to practice, I think this could be beneficial.
sim_txt_improve_exp: This was unrealistic in that no matter what I did, I couldn't convince Ethan to calm down.  I couldn't pull him to the side, I couldn't move next to him and whisper this is inappropriate, I couldn't use hand signals to encourage him to stop.  Even an unruly kid can be encouraged to behave if they know that you are not going to overly punish them for acting out.
sim_txt_concerns: I want this to be beneficial, but I don't know that this was (mostly because I couldn't use other management skills to help Ethan participate), other than having me reconsider setting up classroom norms in the middle of the year.
